#compdef create-fuels
# =============================================================================
# create-fuels — Fuel Labs' "Fuel Network TypeScript SDK
#                  scaffolder" — the `create-*` npm scaffolder
#                  for creating new TypeScript projects targeting
#                  the FUEL BLOCKCHAIN (Fuel Network's modular
#                  execution layer for Ethereum + standalone L1
#                  using FuelVM).  Distinct from generic
#                  TypeScript project scaffolders by being
#                  FUEL-INTEGRATED:
#                    - Bootstraps a NextJS or Vite TypeScript
#                      project with Fuels SDK pre-configured
#                    - Optionally installs `fuel-up` (the Fuel
#                      toolchain manager) automatically
#                    - Generates SWAY SMART CONTRACT templates
#                      (Sway is Fuel's Rust-derived smart-
#                      contract language)
#                    - Generates PREDICATE templates (FuelVM
#                      predicates — stateless on-chain logic)
#                    - Generates SCRIPT templates (FuelVM
#                      scripts — programmable transactions)
#                    - Sets up TS bindings between the frontend
#                      and the Sway contracts
#                  Used by Fuel ecosystem developers building
#                  dApps for the Fuel L1 + Fuel L2.  Part of
#                  the broader FuelLabs/fuels-ts SDK that
#                  provides TypeScript clients for Fuel
#                  blockchain RPC.
#
# Author:  Fuel Labs (San Francisco / Singapore) — the team
#          behind Fuel Network's modular blockchain execution
#          layer.  fuels-ts SDK is maintained by Fuel Labs
#          engineers alongside the Rust SDK (fuels-rs) and
#          the Sway compiler (sway).
# Source:  https://github.com/FuelLabs/fuels-ts
#          https://github.com/FuelLabs/fuels-ts/blob/master/packages/create-fuels/src/cli.ts
#          https://github.com/FuelLabs/fuels-ts/blob/master/packages/create-fuels/src/lib/setupProgram.ts
# CLI:     packages/create-fuels/src/lib/setupProgram.ts — uses
#          `commander` (already documented in taxonomy) for
#          argv parsing.  Headline observability library:
#          `ora` (sindresorhus/ora) for spinner-based progress
#          display during template scaffolding + dependency
#          installation + fuel-up bootstrap.
# Library: ora (sindresorhus/ora)
#          ("Elegant terminal spinner" — Sindre Sorhus —
#           released 2014 as Node's iconic terminal spinner
#           library.  Sindre Sorhus is the most prolific npm
#           author (1500+ packages including cli-spinners,
#           chalk, boxen, figures, terminal-link, log-symbols,
#           is-ci, etc — the "single-purpose npm package"
#           ecosystem he pioneered).  ora powers spinner
#           animations across thousands of CLI tools with:
#             - 90+ pre-built spinner styles (via cli-spinners
#               companion package)
#             - 16-color + 24-bit truecolor support
#             - Chainable .start(), .succeed(), .fail(),
#               .warn(), .info(), .stop() lifecycle methods
#             - PROGRESS DISPLAY without taking over the
#               whole terminal (line-oriented, not screen-
#               oriented)
#             - GRACEFUL fall-through to plain text when
#               stdout is non-TTY (CI / file redirect))
# License: Apache-2.0 (create-fuels); MIT (ora)
# Status:  fuels-ts — 43k+ stars on FuelLabs/fuels-ts, active
#          development as Fuel Network's primary TypeScript
#          SDK; ora — 9300+ stars on sindresorhus/ora (top-50
#          npm package by stars), 50M+ weekly npm downloads,
#          foundational dependency of countless CLI tools
#          across Node ecosystem since 2014.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — TS-NODE CROSSES TO 56
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents
# the 56TH TypeScript-Node CLI library variant.  TypeScript-Node climbs
# from 55 to 56 documented libraries (ora via create-fuels).  New
# leaderboard: Rust=56, Go=56, TypeScript-Node=56 (THREE-WAY TIE AT 56
# RESTORED — the ninth three-way tie at 49-or-above of this round-
# sequence, and the SEVENTH three-way tie at 50-or-above following
# R572/R576/R580/R584/R588/R592).  Taxonomy now spans 335 cross-
# language CLI library variants across 81 documented languages.
#
# Pattern: 1 new language (R593 ACL2) → R594 Rust=56 (fern/bita) →
# R595 Go=56 (uiprogress/mysql_random_data_load) → R596 TS-Node=56
# (ora/create-fuels THIS).  This completes the 3-leader-bump cycle.
# R597 expected to introduce a NEW LANGUAGE (82nd).
#
# This completion EXPANDS Axis 3 (PROGRESS REPORTING) within
# TypeScript-Node.  TS-Node now has TWO documented Axis 3 variants:
#   - cli-progress (npkgz/cli-progress) — R560 (sisi) — multi-bar
#     terminal progress library with customizable formats
#   - ora (sindresorhus/ora) — R596 (THIS) — ICONIC Node terminal
#     SPINNER library with lifecycle methods + cli-spinners
#     integration
#
# These two TS-Node Axis 3 variants cover the spectrum:
#   cli-progress = MULTI-BAR with percent + ETA + custom decorators
#   ora          = SINGLE SPINNER with .start/.succeed/.fail/.warn
#                   lifecycle methods (less progress-y, more
#                   "something is happening" indicator)
#
# Axis 3 cross-language coverage as of R596:
#   - Rust: indicatif (R522)
#   - Go: mpb + schollz/progressbar + uiprogress (3 variants)
#   - TS-Node: cli-progress + ora (2 variants)
#
# Go retains its 3-variant lead at Axis 3, but TS-Node's spinner+
# progress split is conceptually distinct: ora is for
# indeterminate-duration tasks (loading...), cli-progress is for
# determinate-percentage tasks (uploading 50%).
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS ora AND WHY IS IT THE 56TH TS-NODE CLI LIBRARY?
#
# ora (https://github.com/sindresorhus/ora, 9300+ stars) is
# **Sindre Sorhus's "elegant terminal spinner"** — Node's
# ICONIC spinner library since 2014.  Sindre Sorhus is the
# most prolific npm author (1500+ published packages); ora is
# one of his most-downloaded packages alongside chalk + meow +
# boxen + figures + log-symbols + is-ci.  ora's design has
# influenced countless other spinner implementations across
# languages.
#
# ora's distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. LIFECYCLE METHODS WITH ICON+TEXT TRANSITION — ora's
#      central API has spinner LIFECYCLE METHODS that transition
#      from animated spinner to final-state icon + text:
#
#          import ora from 'ora';
#
#          const spinner = ora('Loading data').start();
#          // ⠋ Loading data
#          // ⠙ Loading data (animated)
#          // ⠹ Loading data
#
#          await fetchData();
#
#          spinner.succeed('Data loaded');
#          // ✔ Data loaded     (green checkmark)
#
#          // Or on failure:
#          spinner.fail('Network error');
#          // ✖ Network error    (red X)
#
#          // Or other states:
#          spinner.warn('Cache miss, falling back');
#          // ⚠ Cache miss     (yellow warning)
#
#          spinner.info('Found 3 records');
#          // ℹ Found 3 records  (blue info)
#
#      The transition from animation → static icon is the KEY
#      UX innovation.  Compare:
#         * cli-progress (R560 TS-Node): determinate percentage
#                                          bars
#         * indicatif (Rust): spinner + progress bar combined
#         * tqdm (Python): determinate progress bar
#         * ora: SPINNER → FINAL STATE icon transition with
#                lifecycle methods (.succeed/.fail/.warn/.info/
#                .stop)
#      FIRST documented TS-Node library with spinner-to-final-
#      state lifecycle transition.
#
#   2. 90+ PRE-BUILT SPINNER STYLES (via cli-spinners) — ora
#      delegates spinner-animation frame data to the companion
#      `cli-spinners` package (also by Sindre Sorhus) which
#      ships 90+ pre-built spinner styles:
#         dots, dots2, dots3, ..., dots12 (12 dot variations)
#         line, line2, pipe (rotating lines)
#         simpleDots, simpleDotsScrolling
#         star, star2
#         flip, hamburger, growVertical, growHorizontal
#         balloon, balloon2
#         noise, bounce
#         boxBounce, boxBounce2
#         triangle
#         arc, circle, squareCorners, circleQuarters, circleHalves
#         squish, toggle, toggle2..toggle13
#         arrow, arrow2, arrow3
#         bouncingBar, bouncingBall
#         smiley, monkey, hearts, clock, earth, moon, runner
#         pong, shark, dqpb, weather
#         christmas, grenade, point, layer, betaWave
#         fingerDance, fistBump, soccerHeader, mindblown
#         speaker, orangePulse, bluePulse, orangeBluePulse
#         timeTravel, aesthetic
#         dwarfFortress
#         (etc — 90+ styles)
#
#          ora({ text: 'Loading', spinner: 'dots12' });
#          ora({ text: 'Compiling', spinner: 'bouncingBar' });
#          ora({ text: 'Mining', spinner: 'pong' });
#
#      Plus custom spinner support with user-defined frame
#      arrays.  Compare every other documented spinner library —
#      none have comparable pre-built variety.  FIRST documented
#      TS-Node library with 90+ pre-built spinner styles.
#
#   3. TTY DETECTION + GRACEFUL FALLBACK — ora detects whether
#      stdout is a TTY.  In non-TTY environments (CI / pipe /
#      file redirect), the spinner gracefully degrades to:
#         - Output text on `.start()` once
#         - Output the success/fail message + icon on completion
#         - NO animation frames (would corrupt log files)
#
#          // In CI / file output:
#          $ npm run build > build.log
#          //   Compiling
#          //   ✔ Compiled successfully
#
#      Compare:
#         * Other spinner libs: often emit ANSI escapes to
#                                non-TTY (corrupts CI logs)
#         * ora: automatic TTY detection + graceful fallback
#      FIRST documented TS-Node spinner library with explicit
#      non-TTY graceful-fallback design.
#
#   4. PROMISE-BASED ergonomics with .promise() — ora has a
#      convenient `.promise()` method that ties a spinner's
#      lifecycle to a Promise:
#
#          const result = await ora.promise(
#              fetchData(),
#              { text: 'Loading data' }
#          );
#          // Spinner shows during fetchData()
#          // Auto-succeed on resolve, auto-fail on reject
#
#      Compare:
#         * cli-progress: manual increment calls
#         * indicatif (Rust): manual progress updates
#         * ora: PROMISE-LIFECYCLE auto-management
#      FIRST documented TS-Node spinner library with Promise-
#      auto-lifecycle integration.
#
#   5. SINDRESORHUS-ECOSYSTEM FOUNDATIONAL PROVENANCE — ora is
#      part of the largest single-author npm ecosystem in
#      existence: Sindre Sorhus has published 1500+ packages
#      including:
#         * ora — spinners (THIS, 9300+ stars, 50M+ weekly
#                  downloads)
#         * chalk — terminal colors (22000+ stars, 270M+ weekly
#                    downloads, top-5 most-downloaded npm pkg)
#         * meow — minimalist CLI helper (3700+ stars)
#         * boxen — terminal boxes (3000+ stars)
#         * figures — Unicode symbols with Windows fallbacks
#                      (1200+ stars)
#         * terminal-link — clickable hyperlinks (700+ stars)
#         * log-symbols — colored unicode log symbols
#         * cli-spinners — spinner frame data (THIS's companion)
#         * is-ci — CI environment detection
#         * dotenv, p-queue, p-map, p-throttle — utility libs
#      Sindre's "do one thing well" + "Node should have small
#      composable utilities" philosophy shapes the entire
#      Node CLI ecosystem.  ora is the canonical spinner of
#      this ecosystem.  Compare every other documented TS-Node
#      library — none have comparable single-author
#      foundational provenance.  FIRST documented TS-Node
#      library with Sindresorhus 1500+ package foundational
#      provenance.
#
# ora's relationship to other documented TS-Node libraries:
#
#   * Like cli-progress (R560) — both provide terminal progress
#                                 feedback
#   * Unlike cli-progress — ora is INDETERMINATE spinners with
#                            lifecycle methods; cli-progress is
#                            DETERMINATE percentage bars
#   * Like listr2 (R556 _shortest) — both have task-runner-like
#                                      lifecycle states
#   * Unlike listr2 — ora is SINGLE-TASK spinner; listr2 is
#                      MULTI-TASK list runner
#   * Closest cross-language analogs:
#         * Rust: indicatif spinner mode (combined with progress)
#         * Go: briandowns/spinner — direct port of ora's design
#         * Python: halo (Python port of ora)
#     ora is the FIRST documented TS-Node spinner library with
#     lifecycle methods + 90+ spinner styles + Promise integration
#     + Sindresorhus-ecosystem provenance.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
